SIMPLE: feast
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Feast
<hw>Feast</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>feste</ets> festival, holiday, feast, OF. <ets>feste</ets>
festival, F. <ets>f⟦ecir⟧te</ets>, fr. L. <ets>festum</ets>, pl.
<ets>festa</ets>, fr. <ets>festus</ets> joyful, festal; of uncertain
origin. Cf. <er>Fair</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, <er>Festal</er>,
<er>F⟦ecir⟧te</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A festival; a holiday; a
solemn, or more commonly, a joyous, anniversary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The seventh day shall be a <qex>feast</qex> to the Lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xiii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now his parents went to Jerusalem every year at the
<qex>feast</qex> of the passover.</q> <rj><qau>Luke ii.
41.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ An Ecclesiastical <ex>feast</ex> is called a
<stype>immovable feast</stype> when it always occurs on the same day of
the year; otherwise it is called a <stype>movable feast</stype>. Easter
is a notable <ex>movable feast</ex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A festive or joyous meal; a grand, ceremonious, or
sumptuous entertainment, of which many guests partake; a banquet
characterized by tempting variety and abundance of food.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Enough is as good as a <qex>feast</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Old
Proverb.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Belshazzar the King made a great <qex>feast</qex> to a thousand of
his lords.</q> <rj><qau>Dan. v. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is partaken of, or shared in, with
delight; something highly agreeable; entertainment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>feast</qex> of reason, and the flow of soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Feast day</b></col>, <cd>a holiday; a day set as a solemn
commemorative festival.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Entertainment; regale; banquet; treat; carousal;
festivity; festival.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Feast</er>, <er>Banquet</er>,
<er>Festival</er>, <er>Carousal</er>. A <xex>feast</xex> sets before us
viands superior in quantity, variety, and abundance; a
<xex>banquet</xex> is a luxurious feast; a <xex>festival</xex> is the
joyful celebration by good cheer of some agreeable event.
<xex>Carousal</xex> is unrestrained indulgence in frolic and
drink.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Feast
<hw>Feast</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Feasted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Feasting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>festen</ets>, cf. OF.
<ets>fester</ets> to rest from work, F. <ets>f⟦ecir⟧ter</ets> to
celebrate a holiday. See <er>Feast</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To eat sumptuously; to dine or sup on rich provisions,
particularly in large companies, and on public festivals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And his sons went and <qex>feasted</qex> in their houses.</q>
<rj><qau>Job. i. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be highly gratified or delighted.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With my love's picture then my eye doth <qex>feast</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Feast
<hw>Feast</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To entertain with
sumptuous provisions; to treat at the table bountifully; <as>as, he was
<ex>feasted</ex> by the king</as>.</def> <rj><au>Hayward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To delight; to gratify; <as>as, to <ex>feast</ex>
the soul</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Feast</qex> your ears with the music a while.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Feaster</ent>⟦br⟧
